<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="249" type="multiple">
<paragraph blockId="2.[237,627,230,280]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">
<heading allCaps="true" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" reason="5">DESCRIPTION AND GEOGRAPHIC DISTRIBUTION</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="249" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[192,312,310,333]" box="[192,312,310,333]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[192,673,364,653]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis box="[211,422,364,387]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[211,418,364,387]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turritellidae" genus="Turritella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="duplicata">Turritella duplicata</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the two-keeled screw shell, for full descriptions of the shell, see 
<bibRefCitation author="REEVE, L. A." bookContentInfo="644 pp." box="[192,337,417,440]" firstAuthor="Reeve" journalOrPublisher="Reeve Benham &amp; Reeve, London" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" refId="ref13823" refString="REEVE, L. A., 1849, Conchologia iconica; or illustrations of the shells of molluscous animals. Vol. 5, Reeve Benham &amp; Reeve, London, 644 pp." title="Conchologia iconica; or illustrations of the shells of molluscous animals" type="book" year="1849">Reeve (1849)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="KIENER, L. C. &amp; P. FISCHER" bookContentInfo="232 pp." box="[391,539,417,440]" editor="L. C. KIENER &amp; P. FISCHER" firstAuthor="Kiener" journalOrPublisher="J. - B. Bailliere &amp; Fils, Paris" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" pagination="1 - 86" refId="ref12440" refString="KIENER, L. C. &amp; P. FISCHER, 1873, Genre Turritelle. (Turritella, LAMK). Pp. 1 - 86, in: L. C. KIENER &amp; P. FISCHER, eds., Species general et iconographie des coquilles vivantes comprenant la collection du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle de Paris: la collection Lamarck, celle du Prince Massena (appartenant maintenant a M. B. Delessert) et les decouvertes recentes des voyageurs: Famille des turbinacees. J. - B. Bailliere &amp; Fils, Paris, 232 pp." title="Genre Turritelle. (Turritella, LAMK)." type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Species general et iconographie des coquilles vivantes comprenant la collection du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle de Paris: la collection Lamarck, celle du Prince Massena (appartenant maintenant a M. B. Delessert) et les decouvertes recentes des voyageurs: Famille des turbinacees." year="1873">Kiener (1873)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[192,673,364,653]" lastBlockId="2.[720,1201,230,493]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">
Shells can reach at least 
<quantity box="[484,572,444,467]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="160.0">160 mm</quantity>
in length and about 
<quantity box="[311,387,470,493]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
in basal diameter, with at least 25 whorls. Our observations on the soft part anatomy confirm the description provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="ALLMON, W. D." box="[221,363,550,573]" firstAuthor="Allmon" journalOrPublisher="Malacologia" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" pagination="159 - 202" part="54" refId="ref10793" refString="ALLMON, W. D., 2011, Natural history of turritelline gastropods (Cerithioidea: Turritellidae): a status report. Malacologia, 54: 159 - 202." title="Natural history of turritelline gastropods (Cerithioidea: Turritellidae): a status report" type="journal article" year="2011">Allmon (2011</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 2), and the illustrations of 
<bibRefCitation author="KIENER, L. C. &amp; P. FISCHER" bookContentInfo="232 pp." box="[192,342,577,600]" editor="L. C. KIENER &amp; P. FISCHER" firstAuthor="Kiener" journalOrPublisher="J. - B. Bailliere &amp; Fils, Paris" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" pagination="1 - 86" refId="ref12440" refString="KIENER, L. C. &amp; P. FISCHER, 1873, Genre Turritelle. (Turritella, LAMK). Pp. 1 - 86, in: L. C. KIENER &amp; P. FISCHER, eds., Species general et iconographie des coquilles vivantes comprenant la collection du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle de Paris: la collection Lamarck, celle du Prince Massena (appartenant maintenant a M. B. Delessert) et les decouvertes recentes des voyageurs: Famille des turbinacees. J. - B. Bailliere &amp; Fils, Paris, 232 pp." title="Genre Turritelle. (Turritella, LAMK)." type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Species general et iconographie des coquilles vivantes comprenant la collection du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle de Paris: la collection Lamarck, celle du Prince Massena (appartenant maintenant a M. B. Delessert) et les decouvertes recentes des voyageurs: Famille des turbinacees." year="1873">Kiener (1873)</bibRefCitation>
, reproduced here in 
<figureCitation box="[565,669,577,600]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="2.[192,249,1570,1593]" captionTargetBox="[197,1200,710,1533]" captionTargetId="figure-291@2.[192,1200,710,1533]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGS. 2–6. Anatomical features of T. duplicata. FIG. 2. Underwater photograph of T. duplicata burying itself. Visible elements of soft part anatomy include: a = outer rim of papillae, b = tentacle with eye, c = snout, d = food groove; FIGS. 3, 4: Sketches of shells of T. duplicata copied from Kiener (1873); FIG. 5: Sketch of the corresponding operculum to the specimen figured in Fig. 4; FIG. 6: Sketch of hard- and soft part anatomy of T. duplicata: a = outer rim of papillae, b = tentacle with eye, c = snout, d = food groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6818523" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6818523/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Figs. 2–6</figureCitation>
. The head-foot has a short, wide snout, and a pair of long cephalic tentacles, each with an eye situated near the base. The foot itself is relatively small, with a ciliated groove on the right side. The aperture is fringed by two rows of non-branching papillae or tentacles, which prevent the entrance of large particles. The operculum is small, permitting the animal to retreat into the shell far enough to vacate the lowest two whorls. Ratios between the diameters of opercula and the respective shell apertures range between 1.8 and 2.3.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="2" pageNumber="249" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[720,971,523,547]" box="[720,971,523,547]" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">Geographic Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[720,1200,577,653]" lastBlockId="3.[192,674,230,333]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="2" pageNumber="249">
Indo-West Pacific: from Madagascar to Indonesia; north to the Gujarat coast of India and the Philippines and south to northern Queensland (
<bibRefCitation author="POUTIERS, J. M." bookContentInfo="686 pp." box="[334,494,230,253]" editor="K. E. CARPENTER &amp; V. H. NIEM" firstAuthor="Poutiers" journalOrPublisher="Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, Rome" pageId="3" pageNumber="250" pagination="363 - 648" refId="ref13596" refString="POUTIERS, J. M., 1998, Gastropods. Pp. 363 - 648, in: K. E. CARPENTER &amp; V. H. NIEM, eds., FAO species identification guide for fishery purposes, The living resources of the western central Pacific. Volume 1. Seaweeds, corals, bivalves and gastropods. Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, Rome, 686 pp." title="Gastropods. Pp" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="FAO species identification guide for fishery purposes, The living resources of the western central Pacific. Volume 1. Seaweeds, corals, bivalves and gastropods" year="1998">Poutiers, 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="SARAVANAKUMAR, A. &amp; J. SESH SEREBIAH &amp; G. THIVAKARAN &amp; M. RAJKUMAR" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Saravanakumar" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Ocean University of China (English Ed.)" pageId="3" pageNumber="250" pagination="303 - 309" part="6" refId="ref13906" refString="SARAVANAKUMAR, A., J. SESH SEREBIAH, G. THIVAKARAN &amp; M. RAJKUMAR, 2007, Benthic macrofaunal assemblage in the arid zone mangroves of Gulf of Kachchh-Gujarat. Journal of Ocean University of China (English Ed.), 6: 303 - 309." title="Benthic macrofaunal assemblage in the arid zone mangroves of Gulf of Kachchh-Gujarat" type="journal article" year="2007">Saravanakumar et al., 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[335,403,257,280]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="3.[192,233,1610,1633]" captionTargetBox="[192,1200,1034,1566]" captionTargetId="figure-412@3.[192,1200,1034,1566]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIG. 7. Known distribution of T. duplicata (hatched area) modified form Poutiers (1998) (Caramagna, 1875; Sundaram et al., 1969; Purchon &amp; Purchon, 1981; Rajagopal et al., 1990; Saravanakumar et al., 2007)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6818525" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6818525/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="250">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). It is known to occur in intertidal waters but maximum depth range is unknown.
</paragraph>
